# Dedicated SSH config for the SLURM status dashboard
# (collect.sh + server.py). Used via:
#     ssh -F ssh_config dash-submit "<cmd>"
#
# WHY THIS EXISTS
#   Keep ONE warm, multiplexed connection reused across every refresh and live
#   log stream, so we almost never pay a full (gateway-hop + key-auth) reconnect
#   on a busy submit node. Fewer handshakes = LESS load on OSU's side AND a
#   steadier connection on ours. Both hops (gateway + submit) are multiplexed.
#
# ISOLATION
#   Dedicated Host aliases + dedicated ControlPaths (dash-gw-* / dash-sub-*) mean
#   this can never collide with or disturb the user's interactive ~/.ssh/config
#   masters. `ssh -F` also makes ssh ignore ~/.ssh/config, so this file is
#   self-contained. Host-key checking still uses the default ~/.ssh/known_hosts.
#
# NODE CHOICE (submit-a / submit-b / submit-c)
#   We deliberately use the generic round-robin name `submit.hpc.engr...`.
#   ControlMaster pins us to whichever node the first connection lands on for the
#   master's lifetime (stable, reuses one connection); if that connection dies,
#   the next reconnect re-rolls the round-robin (automatic failover). We do NOT
#   hard-pin a node -- load shifts across submit nodes, and round-robin DNS is
#   not load-aware anyway.
#
# INSTALL NOTE
#   install.sh generates `ssh_config` from this template by replacing
#   __SLURM_USER__ and __SSH_IDENTITY__ with values from config.env.

Host dash-gateway
    HostName access.engr.oregonstate.edu
    User __SLURM_USER__
    IdentityFile __SSH_IDENTITY__
    IdentitiesOnly yes
    BatchMode yes
    ConnectTimeout 20
    ControlMaster auto
    ControlPath ~/.ssh/cm/dash-gw-%C
    ControlPersist 1800
    ServerAliveInterval 30
    ServerAliveCountMax 4
    TCPKeepAlive yes
    # NOTE: Compression is intentionally OFF. It would shift CPU onto the submit
    # node (the sender compresses) -- and the submit node's scarce resource is
    # CPU/load, not bandwidth. The right way to be gentle is to
    # send LESS (query less often), not to compress what we do send.

Host dash-submit
    HostName submit.hpc.engr.oregonstate.edu
    User __SLURM_USER__
    ProxyJump dash-gateway
    IdentityFile __SSH_IDENTITY__
    IdentitiesOnly yes
    BatchMode yes
    ConnectTimeout 20
    ControlMaster auto
    ControlPath ~/.ssh/cm/dash-sub-%C
    ControlPersist 1800
    ServerAliveInterval 30
    ServerAliveCountMax 4
    TCPKeepAlive yes
    # NOTE: Compression is intentionally OFF. It would shift CPU onto the submit
    # node (the sender compresses) -- and the submit node's scarce resource is
    # CPU/load, not bandwidth. The right way to be gentle is to
    # send LESS (query less often), not to compress what we do send.
